Discrete Logarithm
The discrete logarithm is an integer  satisfying the equation
a^x \equiv b \pmod m
for given integers ,  and .
The discrete logarithm does not always exist, for instance there is no solution to . There is no simple condition to determine if the discrete logarithm exists.
In this article, we describe the Baby-step giant-step algorithm, an algorithm to compute the discrete logarithm proposed by Shanks in 1971, which has the time complexity . This is a meet-in-the-middle algorithm because it uses the technique of separating tasks in half.
Algorithm
Consider the equation:
a^x \equiv b \pmod m,
where  and  are relatively prime.
Let , where  is some pre-selected constant (we will describe how to select  later).  is known as giant step, since increasing it by one increases  by . Similarly,  is known as baby step.
Obviously, any number  in the interval  can be represented in this form, where  and .
Then, the equation becomes:
a^{np - q} \equiv b \pmod m.
Using the fact that  and  are relatively prime, we obtain:
a^{np} \equiv ba^q \pmod m
This new equation can be rewritten in a simplified form:
f_1(p) = f_2(q).
This problem can be solved using the meet-in-the-middle method as follows:

Calculate  for all possible arguments . Sort the array of value-argument pairs.
For all possible arguments , calculate  and look for the corresponding  in the sorted array using binary search.

Complexity
We can calculate  in  using the binary exponentiation algorithm. Similarly for .
In the first step of the algorithm, we need to calculate  for every possible argument  and then sort the values. Thus, this step has complexity:
O\left(\left\lceil \frac{m}{n} \right\rceil \left(\log m + \log \left\lceil \frac{m}{n} \right\rceil \right)\right) = O\left( \left\lceil \frac {m}{n} \right\rceil \log m\right)
In the second step of the algorithm, we need to calculate  for every possible argument  and then do a binary search on the array of values of , thus this step has complexity:
O\left(n \left(\log m + \log \frac{m}{n} \right) \right) = O\left(n \log m\right).
Now, when we add these two complexities, we get  multiplied by the sum of  and , which is minimal when , which means, to achieve optimal performance,  should be chosen such that:
n = \sqrt{m}.
Then, the complexity of the algorithm becomes:
O(\sqrt {m} \log m).
Implementation
The simplest implementation
In the following code, the function powmod calculates  and the function solve produces a proper solution to the problem.
It returns  if there is no solution and returns one of the possible solutions otherwise.
int powmod(int a, int b, int m) {
    int res = 1;
    while (b > 0) {
        if (b & 1) {
            res = (res * 1ll * a) % m;
        }
        a = (a * 1ll * a) % m;
        b >>= 1;
    }
    return res;
}

int solve(int a, int b, int m) {
    a %= m, b %= m;
    int n = sqrt(m) + 1;
    map<int, int> vals;
    for (int p = 1; p <= n; ++p)
        vals[powmod(a, p * n, m)] = p;
    for (int q = 0; q <= n; ++q) {
        int cur = (powmod(a, q, m) * 1ll * b) % m;
        if (vals.count(cur)) {
            int ans = vals[cur] * n - q;
            return ans;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

In this code, we used map from the C++ standard library to store the values of .
Internally, map uses a red-black tree to store values.
Thus this code is a little bit slower than if we had used an array and binary searched, but is much easier to write.
Notice that our code assumes , i.e. the code will compute  as solution for the equation  and also as solution for .
This is an often used convention in algebra, but it's also not universally accepted in all areas.
Sometimes  is simply undefined.
If you don't like our convention, then you need to handle the case  separately:
    if (a == 0)
        return b == 0 ? 1 : -1;

Another thing to note is that, if there are multiple arguments  that map to the same value of , we only store one such argument.
This works in this case because we only want to return one possible solution.
If we need to return all possible solutions, we need to change map<int, int> to, say, map<int, vector<int>>.
We also need to change the second step accordingly.
Improved implementation
A possible improvement is to get rid of binary exponentiation.
This can be done by keeping a variable that is multiplied by  each time we increase  and a variable that is multiplied by  each time we increase .
With this change, the complexity of the algorithm is still the same, but now the  factor is only for the map.
Instead of a map, we can also use a hash table (unordered_map in C++) which has the average time complexity  for inserting and searching.
Problems often ask for the minimum  which satisfies the solution.
It is possible to get all answers and take the minimum, or reduce the first found answer using Euler's theorem, but we can be smart about the order in which we calculate values and ensure the first answer we find is the minimum.
// Returns minimum x for which a ^ x % m = b % m, a and m are coprime.
int solve(int a, int b, int m) {
    a %= m, b %= m;
    int n = sqrt(m) + 1;

    int an = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
        an = (an * 1ll * a) % m;

    unordered_map<int, int> vals;
    for (int q = 0, cur = b; q <= n; ++q) {
        vals[cur] = q;
        cur = (cur * 1ll * a) % m;
    }

    for (int p = 1, cur = 1; p <= n; ++p) {
        cur = (cur * 1ll * an) % m;
        if (vals.count(cur)) {
            int ans = n * p - vals[cur];
            return ans;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

The complexity is  using unordered_map.
When  and  are not coprime
Let , and . Clearly  for every  will be divisible by .
If , there is no solution for .
If , let .

\begin{aligned}
a^x & \equiv b \mod m \\\
(g \alpha) a^{x - 1} & \equiv g \beta \mod g \nu \\\
\alpha a^{x-1} & \equiv \beta \mod \nu
\end{aligned}

The baby-step giant-step algorithm can be easily extended to solve  for .
// Returns minimum x for which a ^ x % m = b % m.
int solve(int a, int b, int m) {
    a %= m, b %= m;
    int k = 1, add = 0, g;
    while ((g = gcd(a, m)) > 1) {
        if (b == k)
            return add;
        if (b % g)
            return -1;
        b /= g, m /= g, ++add;
        k = (k * 1ll * a / g) % m;
    }

    int n = sqrt(m) + 1;
    int an = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
        an = (an * 1ll * a) % m;

    unordered_map<int, int> vals;
    for (int q = 0, cur = b; q <= n; ++q) {
        vals[cur] = q;
        cur = (cur * 1ll * a) % m;
    }

    for (int p = 1, cur = k; p <= n; ++p) {
        cur = (cur * 1ll * an) % m;
        if (vals.count(cur)) {
            int ans = n * p - vals[cur] + add;
            return ans;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

The time complexity remains  as before since the initial reduction to coprime  and  is done in .
