Finding Power of Factorial Divisor
You are given two numbers  and . Find the largest integer  such that  divides .
Prime 
Let's first consider the case of prime . The explicit expression for factorial
n! = 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \ldots (n-1) \cdot n
Note that every -th element of the product is divisible by , i.e. adds  to the answer; the number of such elements is .
Next, every -th element is divisible by , i.e. adds another  to the answer (the first power of  has already been counted in the previous paragraph). The number of such elements is .
And so on, for every  each -th element adds another  to the answer, and there are  such elements.
The final answer is
\Bigl\lfloor\dfrac{n}{k}\Bigr\rfloor + \Bigl\lfloor\dfrac{n}{k^2}\Bigr\rfloor + \ldots + \Bigl\lfloor\dfrac{n}{k^i}\Bigr\rfloor + \ldots
This result is also known as Legendre's formula.
The sum is of course finite, since only approximately the first  elements are not zeros. Thus, the runtime of this algorithm is .
Implementation
int fact_pow (int n, int k) {
    int res = 0;
    while (n) {
        n /= k;
        res += n;
    }
    return res;
}

Composite 
The same idea can't be applied directly. Instead we can factor , representing it as . For each , we find the number of times it is present in  using the algorithm described above - let's call this value . The answer for composite  will be
\min_ {i=1 \ldots m} \dfrac{a_i}{p_i}

