Binary Exponentiation by Factoring
Consider a problem of computing , given integers , ,  and , where  is odd.
The algorithm below allows to solve this problem with  additions and binary operations and a single multiplication by .
Due to the structure of the multiplicative group modulo , any number  such that  can be represented as

x \equiv b^{L(x)} \pmod{2^d},

where . Without loss of generality we assume that , as we can reduce  to  by substituting  and . In this notion,  is represented as

a x^y \equiv a b^{yL(x)} \pmod{2^d}.

The core idea of the algorithm is to simplify the computation of  and  using the fact that we're working modulo . For reasons that will be apparent later on, we'll be working with  rather than , but taken modulo  instead of .
In this article, we will cover the implementation for -bit integers. Let

mbin_log_32(r, x) be a function that computes ;
mbin_exp_32(r, x) be a function that computes ;
mbin_power_odd_32(a, x, y) be a function that computes .

Then mbin_power_odd_32 is implemented as follows:
uint32_t mbin_power_odd_32(uint32_t rem, uint32_t base, uint32_t exp) {
    if (base & 2) {
        /* divider is considered negative */
        base = -base;
        /* check if result should be negative */
        if (exp & 1) {
            rem = -rem;
        }
    }
    return (mbin_exp_32(rem, mbin_log_32(0, base) * exp));
}

Computing 4L(x) from x
Let  be an odd number such that . It can be represented as 

x \equiv (2^{a_1}+1)\dots(2^{a_k}+1) \pmod{2^d},

where . Here  is well-defined for each multiplier, as they're equal to  modulo . Hence,

4L(x) \equiv 4L(2^{a_1}+1)+\dots+4L(2^{a_k}+1) \pmod{2^{d}}.

So, if we precompute  for all , we will be able to compute  for any number .
For 32-bit integers, we can use the following table:
const uint32_t mbin_log_32_table[32] = {
    0x00000000, 0x00000000, 0xd3cfd984, 0x9ee62e18,
    0xe83d9070, 0xb59e81e0, 0xa17407c0, 0xce601f80,
    0xf4807f00, 0xe701fe00, 0xbe07fc00, 0xfc1ff800,
    0xf87ff000, 0xf1ffe000, 0xe7ffc000, 0xdfff8000,
    0xffff0000, 0xfffe0000, 0xfffc0000, 0xfff80000,
    0xfff00000, 0xffe00000, 0xffc00000, 0xff800000,
    0xff000000, 0xfe000000, 0xfc000000, 0xf8000000,
    0xf0000000, 0xe0000000, 0xc0000000, 0x80000000,
};

On practice, a slightly different approach is used than described above. Rather than finding the factorization for , we will consequently multiply  with  until we turn it into  modulo . In this way, we will find the representation of , that is

x (2^{a_1}+1)\dots(2^{a_k}+1) \equiv 1 \pmod {2^d}.

To do this, we iterate over  such that . If the current  has -th bit set, we multiply  with , which is conveniently done in C++ as x = x + (x << n). This won't change bits lower than , but will turn the -th bit to zero, because  is odd.
With all this in mind, the function mbin_log_32(r, x) is implemented as follows:
uint32_t mbin_log_32(uint32_t r, uint32_t x) {
    uint8_t n;

    for (n = 2; n < 32; n++) {
        if (x & (1 << n)) {
            x = x + (x << n);
            r -= mbin_log_32_table[n];
        }
    }

    return r;
}

Note that , so instead of adding , we subtract it from , which initially equates to .
Computing x from 4L(x)
Note that for  it holds that

(a 2^{k}+1)^2 = a^2 2^{2k} +a 2^{k+1}+1 = b2^{k+1}+1,

from which (by repeated squaring) we can deduce that

(2^a+1)^{2^b} \equiv 1 \pmod{2^{a+b}}.

Applying this result to  and  we deduce that the multiplicative order of  is a divisor of .
This, in turn, means that  must be divisible by , as the order of  is  and the order of  is , where  is the highest power of  that divides , so we need

2^{d-k} \equiv 0 \pmod{2^{d-2-v}},

thus  must be greater or equal than . This is a bit ugly and to mitigate this we said in the beginning that we multiply  by . Now if we know , we can uniquely decomposing it into a sum of  by consequentially checking bits in . If the -th bit is set to , we will multiply the result with  and reduce the current  by .
Thus, mbin_exp_32 is implemented as follows:
uint32_t mbin_exp_32(uint32_t r, uint32_t x) {
    uint8_t n;

    for (n = 2; n < 32; n++) {
        if (x & (1 << n)) {
            r = r + (r << n);
            x -= mbin_log_32_table[n];
        }
    }

    return r;
}

Further optimizations
It is possible to halve the number of iterations if you note that  and that for  it holds that

(2^n+1)^2 \equiv 2^{2n} + 2^{n+1}+1 \equiv 2^{n+1}+1 \pmod{2^d},

which allows to deduce that  for . So, you could simplify the algorithm by only going up to  and then use the fact above to compute the remaining part with bitwise operations:
uint32_t mbin_log_32(uint32_t r, uint32_t x) {
    uint8_t n;

    for (n = 2; n != 16; n++) {
        if (x & (1 << n)) {
            x = x + (x << n);
            r -= mbin_log_32_table[n];
        }
    }

    r -= (x & 0xFFFF0000);

    return r;
}

uint32_t mbin_exp_32(uint32_t r, uint32_t x) {
    uint8_t n;

    for (n = 2; n != 16; n++) {
        if (x & (1 << n)) {
            r = r + (r << n);
            x -= mbin_log_32_table[n];
        }
    }

    r *= 1 - (x & 0xFFFF0000);

    return r;
}

Computing logarithm table
To compute log-table, one could modify the Pohlig–Hellman algorithm for the case when modulo is a power of .
Our main task here is to compute  such that , where  and  is a number of kind . 
Squaring both parts  times we arrive to

g^{2^k x} \equiv y^{2^k} \pmod{2^d}.

Note that the order of  is not greater than  (in fact, than , but we will stick to  for convenience), hence using  we will have either  or  on the left hand side which allows us to determine the smallest bit of  by comparing  to . Now assume that , where  is a known part and  is not yet known. Then

g^{x_0+2^k x_1} \equiv y \pmod{2^d}.

Multiplying both parts with , we get

g^{2^k x_1} \equiv (g^{-x_0} y) \pmod{2^d}.

Now, squaring both sides  times we can obtain the next bit of , eventually recovering all its bits.
