Additionally we can precompute the bit-reversal permutation beforehand.
This is especially useful when the size  is the same for all calls.
But even when we only have three calls (which are necessary for multiplying two polynomials), the effect is noticeable.
Also we can precompute all roots of unity and their powers.
Number theoretic transform
Now we switch the objective a little bit.
We still want to multiply two polynomials in  time, but this time we want to compute the coefficients modulo some prime number .
Of course for this task we can use the normal DFT and apply the modulo operator to the result.
However, doing so might lead to rounding errors, especially when dealing with large numbers.
The number theoretic transform (NTT) has the advantage, that it only works with integer, and therefore the result are guaranteed to be correct.
The discrete Fourier transform is based on complex numbers, and the -th roots of unity.
To efficiently compute it, we extensively use properties of the roots (e.g. that there is one root that generates all other roots by exponentiation).
But the same properties hold for the -th roots of unity in modular arithmetic.
A -th root of unity under a primitive field is such a number  that satisfies:
\begin{align}
(w_n)^n &= 1 \pmod{p}, \\
(w_n)^k &\ne 1 \pmod{p}, \quad 1 \le k < n.
\end{align}
The other  roots can be obtained as powers of the root .
To apply it in the fast Fourier transform algorithm, we need a root to exist for some , which is a power of , and also for all smaller powers.
We can notice the following interesting property:
\begin{align}
(w_n^2)^m = w_n^n &= 1 \pmod{p}, \quad \text{with } m = \frac{n}{2}\\
(w_n^2)^k = w_n^{2k} &\ne 1 \pmod{p}, \quad 1 \le k < m.
\end{align}
Thus if  is a -th root of unity, then  is a -th root of unity.
And consequently for all smaller powers of two there exist roots of the required degree, and they can be computed using .
For computing the inverse DFT, we need the inverse  of .
But for a prime modulus the inverse always exists.
Thus all the properties that we need from the complex roots are also available in modular arithmetic, provided that we have a large enough module  for which a -th root of unity exists.
For example we can take the following values: module , .
If this module is not enough, we need to find a different pair.
We can use that fact that for modules of the form  (and  is prime), there always exists the -th root of unity.
It can be shown that  is such a -th root of unity, where  is a primitive root of .
const int mod = 7340033;
const int root = 5;
const int root_1 = 4404020;
const int root_pw = 1 << 20;

void fft(vector<int> & a, bool invert) {
    int n = a.size();

    for (int i = 1, j = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int bit = n >> 1;
        for (; j & bit; bit >>= 1)
            j ^= bit;
        j ^= bit;

        if (i < j)
            swap(a[i], a[j]);
    }

    for (int len = 2; len <= n; len <<= 1) {
        int wlen = invert ? root_1 : root;
        for (int i = len; i < root_pw; i <<= 1)
            wlen = (int)(1LL * wlen * wlen % mod);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i += len) {
            int w = 1;
            for (int j = 0; j < len / 2; j++) {
                int u = a[i+j], v = (int)(1LL * a[i+j+len/2] * w % mod);
                a[i+j] = u + v < mod ? u + v : u + v - mod;
                a[i+j+len/2] = u - v >= 0 ? u - v : u - v + mod;
                w = (int)(1LL * w * wlen % mod);
            }
        }
    }

    if (invert) {
        int n_1 = inverse(n, mod);
        for (int & x : a)
            x = (int)(1LL * x * n_1 % mod);
    }
}

Here the function inverse computes the modular inverse (see Modular Multiplicative Inverse).
The constants mod, root, root_pw determine the module and the root, and root_1 is the inverse of root modulo mod.
In practice this implementation is slower than the implementation using complex numbers (due to the huge number of modulo operations), but it has some advantages such as less memory usage and no rounding errors.
Multiplication with arbitrary modulus
Here we want to achieve the same goal as in previous section.
Multiplying two polynomial  and , and computing the coefficients modulo some number .
The number theoretic transform only works for certain prime numbers.
What about the case when the modulus is not of the desired form?
One option would be to perform multiple number theoretic transforms with different prime numbers of the form , then apply the Chinese Remainder Theorem to compute the final coefficients.
Another options is to distribute the polynomials  and  into two smaller polynomials each
\begin{align}
A(x) &= A_1(x) + A_2(x) \cdot C \\
B(x) &= B_1(x) + B_2(x) \cdot C
\end{align}
with .
Then the product of  and  can then be represented as:
A(x) \cdot B(x) = A_1(x) \cdot B_1(x) + \left(A_1(x) \cdot B_2(x) + A_2(x) \cdot B_1(x)\right)\cdot C + \left(A_2(x) \cdot B_2(x)\right)\cdot C^2
The polynomials , ,  and  contain only coefficients smaller than , therefore the coefficients of all the appearing products are smaller than , which is usually small enough to handle with typical floating point types.
This approach therefore requires computing the products of polynomials with smaller coefficients (by using the normal FFT and inverse FFT), and then the original product can be restored using modular addition and multiplication in  time.
