Longest increasing subsequence
We are given an array with  numbers: .
The task is to find the longest, strictly increasing, subsequence in .
Formally we look for the longest sequence of indices  such that
i_1 < i_2 < \dots < i_k,\quad
a[i_1] < a[i_2] < \dots < a[i_k]
In this article we discuss multiple algorithms for solving this task.
Also we will discuss some other problems, that can be reduced to this problem.
Solution in  with dynamic programming
Dynamic programming is a very general technique that allows to solve a huge class of problems.
Here we apply the technique for our specific task.
First we will search only for the length of the longest increasing subsequence, and only later learn how to restore the subsequence itself.
Finding the length
To accomplish this task, we define an array , where  is the length of the longest increasing subsequence that ends in the element at index .

Example
\begin{array}{ll}
a &= \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5, 2, 0, 7, 9, 1\} \\
d &= \{1, 1, 2, 3, 3, 1, 1, 4, 5, 2\}
\end{array}
The longest increasing subsequence that ends at index 4 is  with a length of 3, the longest ending at index 8 is either  or , both having length 5, and the longest ending at index 9 is  having length 2.

We will compute this array gradually: first , then , and so on.
After this array is computed, the answer to the problem will be the maximum value in the array .
So let the current index be .
I.e. we want to compute the value  and all previous values  are already known.
Then there are two options:

: the required subsequence consists only of the element .

: The subsequence will end at , and right before it will be some number  with  and .
It's easy to see, that the subsequence ending in  will itself be one of the longest increasing subsequences that ends in .
The number  just extends that longest increasing subsequence by one number.
Therefore, we can just iterate over all  with , and take the longest sequence that we get by appending  to the longest increasing subsequence ending in .
The longest increasing subsequence ending in  has length , extending it by one gives the length .
d[i] = \max_{\substack{j < i \\\\ a[j] < a[i]}} \left(d[j] + 1\right)

If we combine these two cases we get the final answer for :
d[i] = \max\left(1, \max_{\substack{j < i \\\\ a[j] < a[i]}} \left(d[j] + 1\right)\right)
Implementation
Here is an implementation of the algorithm described above, which computes the length of the longest increasing subsequence.
int lis(vector<int> const& a) {
    int n = a.size();
    vector<int> d(n, 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (a[j] < a[i])
                d[i] = max(d[i], d[j] + 1);
        }
    }

    int ans = d[0];
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        ans = max(ans, d[i]);
    }
    return ans;
}

Restoring the subsequence
So far we only learned how to find the length of the subsequence, but not how to find the subsequence itself.
To be able to restore the subsequence we generate an additional auxiliary array  that we will compute alongside the array .
 will be the index  of the second last element in the longest increasing subsequence ending in .
In other words the index  is the same index  at which the highest value  was obtained.
This auxiliary array  points in some sense to the ancestors.
Then to derive the subsequence, we just start at the index  with the maximal , and follow the ancestors until we deduced the entire subsequence, i.e. until we reach the element with .
Implementation of restoring
We will change the code from the previous sections a little bit.
We will compute the array  alongside , and afterwards compute the subsequence.
For convenience we originally assign the ancestors with .
For elements with , the ancestors value will remain , which will be slightly more convenient for restoring the subsequence.
vector<int> lis(vector<int> const& a) {
    int n = a.size();
    vector<int> d(n, 1), p(n, -1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (a[j] < a[i] && d[i] < d[j] + 1) {
                d[i] = d[j] + 1;
                p[i] = j;
            }
        }
    }

    int ans = d[0], pos = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        if (d[i] > ans) {
            ans = d[i];
            pos = i;
        }
    }

    vector<int> subseq;
    while (pos != -1) {
        subseq.push_back(a[pos]);
        pos = p[pos];
    }
    reverse(subseq.begin(), subseq.end());
    return subseq;
}

Alternative way of restoring the subsequence
It is also possible to restore the subsequence without the auxiliary array .
We can simply recalculate the current value of  and also see how the maximum was reached.
This method leads to a slightly longer code, but in return we save some memory.
Solution in  with dynamic programming and binary search
In order to obtain a faster solution for the problem, we construct a different dynamic programming solution that runs in , and then later improve it to .
We will use the dynamic programming array .
This time  doesn't correspond to the element  or to a prefix of the array. 
 will be the smallest element at which an increasing subsequence of length  ends.
Initially we assume  and for all other lengths .
We will again gradually process the numbers, first , then , etc, and in each step maintain the array  so that it is up to date.

Example
Given the array , here are all their prefixes and their dynamic programming array.
Notice, that the values of the array don't always change at the end.

\begin{array}{ll}
\text{prefix} = \{\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, \infty, \dots\}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 8, \infty, \dots\}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 3, \infty, \dots\}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 3, 4, \infty, \dots\}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 3, 4, 6, \infty, \dots\}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 3, 4, 5, \infty, \dots\}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5, 2\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 2, 4, 5, \infty, \dots \}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5, 2, 0\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 0, 4, 5, \infty, \dots \}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5, 2, 0, 7\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 0, 4, 5, 7, \infty, \dots \}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5, 2, 0, 7, 9\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 0, 4, 5, 7, 9, \infty, \dots \}\\
\text{prefix} = \{8, 3, 4, 6, 5, 2, 0, 7, 9, 1\} &\quad d = \{-\infty, 0, 1, 5, 7, 9, \infty, \dots \}\\
\end{array}

When we process , we can ask ourselves.
What have the conditions to be, that we write the current number  into the  array?
We set , if there is a longest increasing sequence of length  that ends in , and there is no longest increasing sequence of length  that ends in a smaller number.
Similar to the previous approach, if we remove the number  from the longest increasing sequence of length , we get another longest increasing sequence of length .
So we want to extend a longest increasing sequence of length  by the number , and obviously the longest increasing sequence of length  that ends with the smallest element will work the best, in other words the sequence of length  that ends in element .
There is a longest increasing sequence of length  that we can extend with the number , exactly if .
So we can just iterate over each length , and check if we can extend a longest increasing sequence of length  by checking the criteria.
Additionally we also need to check, if we maybe have already found a longest increasing sequence of length  with a smaller number at the end.
So we only update if .
After processing all the elements of  the length of the desired subsequence is the largest  with .
int lis(vector<int> const& a) {
    int n = a.size();
    const int INF = 1e9;
    vector<int> d(n+1, INF);
    d[0] = -INF;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int l = 1; l <= n; l++) {
            if (d[l-1] < a[i] && a[i] < d[l])
                d[l] = a[i];
        }
    }

    int ans = 0;
    for (int l = 0; l <= n; l++) {
        if (d[l] < INF)
            ans = l;
    }
    return ans;
}

We now make two important observations.

The array  will always be sorted: 
     for all .
This is trivial, as you can just remove the last element from the increasing subsequence of length , and you get a increasing subsequence of length  with a smaller ending number.

The element  will only update at most one value .
This follows immediately from the above implementation.
There can only be one place in the array with .

Thus we can find this element in the array  using binary search in .
In fact we can simply look in the array  for the first number that is strictly greater than , and we try to update this element in the same way as the above implementation.
Implementation
This gives us the improved  implementation:
int lis(vector<int> const& a) {
    int n = a.size();
    const int INF = 1e9;
    vector<int> d(n+1, INF);
    d[0] = -INF;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int l = upper_bound(d.begin(), d.end(), a[i]) - d.begin();
        if (d[l-1] < a[i] && a[i] < d[l])
            d[l] = a[i];
    }

    int ans = 0;
    for (int l = 0; l <= n; l++) {
        if (d[l] < INF)
            ans = l;
    }
    return ans;
}

Restoring the subsequence
It is also possible to restore the subsequence using this approach.
This time we have to maintain two auxiliary arrays.
One that tells us the index of the elements in .
And again we have to create an array of "ancestors" .
 will be the index of the previous element for the optimal subsequence ending in element .
It's easy to maintain these two arrays in the course of iteration over the array  alongside the computations of .
And at the end it is not difficult to restore the desired subsequence using these arrays.
Solution in  with data structures
Instead of the above method for computing the longest increasing subsequence in  we can also solve the problem in a different way: using some simple data structures.
Let's go back to the first method.
Remember that  is the value  with  and .
Thus if we define an additional array  such that
t[a[i]] = d[i],
then the problem of computing the value  is equivalent to finding the maximum value in a prefix of the array :
d[i] = \max\left(t[0 \dots a[i] - 1] + 1\right)
The problem of finding the maximum of a prefix of an array (which changes) is a standard problem that can be solved by many different data structures. 
For instance we can use a Segment tree or a Fenwick tree.
This method has obviously some shortcomings:
in terms of length and complexity of the implementation this approach will be worse than the method using binary search.
In addition if the input numbers  are especially large, then we would have to use some tricks, like compressing the numbers (i.e. renumber them from  to ), or use a dynamic segment tree (only generate the branches of the tree that are important).
Otherwise the memory consumption will be too high.
On the other hand this method has also some advantages:
with this method you don't have to think about any tricky properties in the dynamic programming solution.
And this approach allows us to generalize the problem very easily (see below).
Related tasks
Here are several problems that are closely related to the problem of finding the longest increasing subsequence.
Longest non-decreasing subsequence
This is in fact nearly the same problem.
Only now it is allowed to use identical numbers in the subsequence.
The solution is essentially also nearly the same.
We just have to change the inequality signs, and make a slight modification to the binary search.
Number of longest increasing subsequences
We can use the first discussed method, either the  version or the version using data structures.
We only have to additionally store in how many ways we can obtain longest increasing subsequences ending in the values .
The number of ways to form a longest increasing subsequences ending in  is the sum of all ways for all longest increasing subsequences ending in  where  is maximal.
There can be multiple such , so we need to sum all of them.
Using a Segment tree this approach can also be implemented in .
It is not possible to use the binary search approach for this task.
Smallest number of non-increasing subsequences covering a sequence
For a given array with  numbers  we have to colorize the numbers in the smallest number of colors, so that each color forms a non-increasing subsequence.
To solve this, we notice that the minimum number of required colors is equal to the length of the longest increasing subsequence.
Proof:
We need to prove the duality of these two problems.
Let's denote by  the length of the longest increasing subsequence and by  the least number of non-increasing subsequences that form a cover.
We need to prove that .
It is clear that  is not possible, because if we have  strictly increasing elements, than no two can be part of the same non-increasing subsequence.
Therefore we have .
We now show that  is not possible by contradiction.
Suppose that .
Then we consider any optimal set of  non-increasing subsequences.
We transform this in set in the following way:
as long as there are two such subsequences such that the first begins before the second subsequence, and the first sequence start with a number greater than or equal to the second, then we unhook this starting number and attach it to the beginning of second.
After a finite number of steps we have  subsequences, and their starting numbers will form an increasing subsequence of length .
Since we assumed that  we reached a contradiction.
Thus it follows that .
Restoring the sequences:
The desired partition of the sequence into subsequences can be done greedily.
I.e. go from left to right and assign the current number or that subsequence ending with the minimal number which is greater than or equal to the current one.
