Minimum Enclosing Circle
Consider the following problem:

Library Checker - Minimum Enclosing Circle
You're given  points .
For each , find whether it lies on the circumference of the minimum enclosing circle of .

Here, by the minimum enclosing circle (MEC) we mean a circle with minimum possible radius that contains all the  points, inside the circle or on its boundary. This problem has a simple randomized solution that, on first glance, looks like it would run in , but actually works in  expected time.
To better understand the reasoning below, we should immediately note that the solution to the problem is unique:

Why is the MEC unique?
Consider the following setup: Let  be the radius of the MEC. We draw a circle of radius  around each of the points . Geometrically, the centers of circles that have radius  and cover all the points  form the intersection of all  circles.
Now, if the intersection is just a single point, this already proves that it is unique. Otherwise, the intersection is a shape of non-zero area, so we can reduce  by a tiny bit, and still have non-empty intersection, which contradicts the assumption that  was the minimum possible radius of the enclosing circle.
With a similar logic, we can also show the uniqueness of the MEC if we additionally demand that it passes through a given specific point  or two points  and  (it is also unique because its radius uniquely defines it).
Alternatively, we can also assume that there are two MECs, and then notice that their intersection (which contains the points  already) must have a smaller diameter than initial circles, and thus can be covered with a smaller circle.

Welzl's algorithm
For brevity, let's denote  to be the MEC of , and let .
The algorithm, initially proposed by Welzl in 1991, goes as follows:

Apply a random permutation to the input sequence of points.
Maintain the current candidate to be the MEC , starting with .
Iterate over  and check if .
If  it means that  is the MEC of .
Otherwise, assign  and iterate over  and check if .
If , then  is the MEC of  among circles that pass through .
Otherwise, assign  and iterate over  and check if .
If , then  is the MEC of  among circles that pass through  and .
Otherwise,  is the MEC of  among circles that pass through  and .

We can see that each level of nestedness here has an invariant to maintain (that  is the MEC among circles that also pass through additionally given ,  or  points), and whenever the inner loop closes, its invariant becomes equivalent to the invariant of the current iteration of its parent loop. This, in turn, ensures the correctness of the algorithm as a whole.
Omitting some technical details, for now, the whole algorithm can be implemented in C++ as follows:
struct point {...};

// Is represented by 2 or 3 points on its circumference
struct mec {...};

bool inside(mec const& C, point p) {
    return ...;
}

// Choose some good generator of randomness for the shuffle
mt19937_64 gen(...);
mec enclosing_circle(vector<point> &p) {
    int n = p.size();
    ranges::shuffle(p, gen);
    auto C = mec{p[0], p[1]};
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if(!inside(C, p[i])) {
            C = mec{p[i], p[0]};
            for(int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                if(!inside(C, p[j])) {
                    C = mec{p[i], p[j]};
                    for(int k = 0; k < j; k++) {
                        if(!inside(C, p[k])) {
                            C = mec{p[i], p[j], p[k]};
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return C;
}

Now, it is to be expected that checking that a point  is inside the MEC of  or  points can be done in  (we will discuss this later on). But even then, the algorithm above looks as if it would take  in the worst case just because of all the nested loops. So, how come we claimed the linear expected runtime? Let's figure out!
Complexity analysis
For the inner-most loop (over ), clearly its expected runtime is  operations. What about the loop over ?
It only triggers the next loop if  is on the boundary of the MEC of  that also passes through point , and removing  would further shrink the circle. Of all points in  there can only be at most  points with such property, because if there are more than  points from  on the boundary, it means that after removing any of them, there will still be at least  points on the boundary, sufficient to uniquely define the circle.
In other words, after initial random shuffle, there is at most  probability that we get one of the at most two unlucky points as . Summing it up over all  from  to , we get the expected runtime of

\sum\limits_{j=1}^i \frac{2}{j} \cdot O(j) = O(i).

In exactly same fashion we can now also prove that the outermost loop has expected runtime of .
Checking that a point is in the MEC of 2 or 3 points
Let's now figure out the implementation detail of point and mec. In this problem, it turns out to be particularly useful to use std::complex as a class for points:
using ftype = int64_t;
using point = complex<ftype>;

As a reminder, a complex number is a number of type , where  and . In C++, such complex number is represented by a 2-dimensional point . Complex numbers already implement basic component-wise linear operations (addition, multiplication by a real number), but also their multiplication and division carry certain geometric meaning.
Without going in too much detail, we will note the most important property for this particular task: Multiplying two complex numbers adds up their polar angles (counted from  counter-clockwise), and taking a conjugate (i.e. changing  into ) multiplies the polar angle with . This allows us to formulate some very simple criteria for whether a point  is inside the MEC of  or  specific points.
MEC of 2 points
For  points  and , their MEC is simply the circle centered at  with the radius , in other words the circle that has  as a diameter. To check if  is inside this circle we simply need to check that the angle between  and  is not acute.

Inner angles are obtuse, external angles are acute and angles on the circumference are right

Equivalently, we need to check that

I_0=(b-z)\overline{(a-z)}

doesn't have a positive real coordinate (corresponding to points that have a polar angle between  and ).
MEC of 3 points
Adding  to the triangle  will make it a quadrilateral. Consider the following expression:

\angle azb + \angle bca

In a cyclic quadrilateral, if  and  are from the same side of , then the angles are equal, and will add up to  when summed up signed (i.e. positive if counter-clockwise and negative if clockwise). Correspondingly, if  and  are on the opposite sides, the angles will add up to .

Adjacent inscribed angles are same, opposing angles complement to 180 degrees

In terms of complex numbers, we can note that  is the polar angle of  and  is the polar angle of . Thus, we can conclude that  is the polar angle of

I_1 = (b-z) \overline{(a-z)} (a-c) \overline{(b-c)}

If the angle is  or , it means that the imaginary part of  is , otherwise we can deduce whether  is inside or outside of the enclosing circle of  by checking the sign of the imaginary part of . Positive imaginary part corresponds to positive angles, and negative imaginary part corresponds to negative angles.
But which one of them means that  is inside or outside of the circle? As we already noticed, having  inside the circle generally increases the magnitude of , while having it outside the circle decreases it. As such, we have the following 4 cases:

,  on the same side of  as . Then, , and  for points inside the circle.
,  on the same side of  as . Then, , and  for points inside the circle.
,  on the opposite side of  to . Then,  and  for points inside the circle.
,  on the opposite side of  to . Then,  and  for points inside the circle.

In other words, if  is positive, points inside the circle will have , otherwise they will have , assuming that we normalize the angles between  and . This, in turn, can be checked by the signs of imaginary parts of  and .
Note: As we multiply four complex numbers to get , the intermediate coefficients can be as large as , where  is the largest coordinate magnitude in the input. On the bright side, if the input is integer, both checks above can be done fully in integers.
Implementation
Now, to actually implement the check, we should first decide how to represent the MEC. As our criteria work with the points directly, a natural and efficient way to do this is to say that MEC is directly represented as a pair or triple of points that defines it:
using mec = variant<
    array<point, 2>,
    array<point, 3>
>;

Now, we can use std::visit to efficiently deal with both cases in accordance with criteria above:
/* I < 0 if z inside C,
   I > 0 if z outside C,
   I = 0 if z on the circumference of C */
ftype indicator(mec const& C, point z) {
    return visit([&](auto &&C) {
        point a = C[0], b = C[1];
        point I0 = (b - z) * conj(a - z);
        if constexpr (size(C) == 2) {
            return real(I0);
        } else {
            point c = C[2];
            point I2 = (a - c) * conj(b - c);
            point I1 = I0 * I2;
            return imag(I2) < 0 ? -imag(I1) : imag(I1);
        }
    }, C);
}

bool inside(mec const& C, point p) {
    return indicator(C, p) <= 0;
}

Now, we can finally ensure that everything works by submitting the problem to the Library Checker: #308668.
