Finding the nearest pair of points
Problem statement
Given  points on the plane. Each point  is defined by its coordinates . It is required to find among them two such points, such that the distance between them is minimal:
 \min_{\scriptstyle i, j=0 \ldots n-1,\atop \scriptstyle i \neq j } \rho (p_i, p_j). 
We take the usual Euclidean distances:
 \rho (p_i,p_j) = \sqrt{(x_i-x_j)^2 + (y_i-y_j)^2} .
The trivial algorithm - iterating over all pairs and calculating the distance for each — works in . 
The algorithm running in time  is described below. This algorithm was proposed by Shamos and Hoey in 1975. (Source: Ch. 5 Notes of Algorithm Design by Kleinberg & Tardos, also see here) Preparata and Shamos also showed that this algorithm is optimal in the decision tree model.
Algorithm
We construct an algorithm according to the general scheme of divide-and-conquer algorithms: the algorithm is designed as a recursive function, to which we pass a set of points; this recursive function splits this set in half, calls itself recursively on each half, and then performs some operations to combine the answers. The operation of combining consist of  detecting the cases when one point of the optimal solution fell into one half, and the other point into the other (in this case, recursive calls from each of the halves cannot detect this pair separately). The main difficulty, as always in case of divide and conquer algorithms, lies in the effective implementation of the merging stage. If a set of  points is passed to the recursive function, then the merge stage should work no more than , then the asymptotics of the whole algorithm  will be found from the equation:
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n).
The solution to this equation, as is known, is 
So, we proceed on to the construction of the algorithm. In order to come to an effective implementation of the merge stage in the future, we will divide the set of points into two subsets, according to their -coordinates: In fact, we draw some vertical line dividing the set of points into two subsets of approximately the same size. It is convenient to make such a partition as follows: We sort the points in the standard way as pairs of numbers, ie.:
p_i < p_j \Longleftrightarrow (x_i < x_j) \lor \Big(\left(x_i = x_j\right) \wedge \left(y_i < y_j \right) \Big) 
Then take the middle point after sorting , and all the points before it and the  itself are assigned to the first half, and all the points after it - to the second half:
A_1 = \{p_i \ | \ i = 0 \ldots m \}
A_2 = \{p_i \ | \ i = m + 1 \ldots n-1 \}.
Now, calling recursively on each of the sets  and , we will find the answers  and  for each of the halves. And take the best of them: .
Now we need to make a merge stage, i.e. we try to find such pairs of points, for which the distance between which is less than  and one point is lying in  and the other in .
It is obvious that it is sufficient to consider only those points that are separated from the vertical line by a distance less than , i.e. the set  of the points considered at this stage is equal to:
B = \{ p_i\ | \ | x_i - x_m\ | < h \}.
For each point in the set , we try to find the points that are closer to it than . For example, it is sufficient to consider only those points whose -coordinate differs by no more than . Moreover, it makes no sense to consider those points whose -coordinate is greater than the -coordinate of the current point. Thus, for each point  we define the set of considered points  as follows:
C(p_i) = \{ p_j\ |\ p_j \in B,\ \ y_i - h < y_j \le y_i \}.
If we sort the points of the set  by -coordinate, it will be very easy to find : these are several points in a row ahead to the point .
So, in the new notation, the merging stage looks like this: build a set , sort the points in it by -coordinate, then for each point  consider all points , and for each pair  calculate the distance and compare with the current best distance.
At first glance, this is still a non-optimal algorithm: it seems that the sizes of sets  will be of order , and the required asymptotics will not work. However, surprisingly, it can be proved that the size of each of the sets  is a quantity , i.e. it does not exceed some small constant regardless of the points themselves. Proof of this fact is given in the next section.
Finally, we pay attention to the sorting, which the above algorithm contains: first,sorting by pairs , and then second, sorting the elements of the set  by . In fact, both of these sorts inside the recursive function can be eliminated (otherwise we would not reach the  estimate for the merging stage, and the general asymptotics of the algorithm would be ). It is easy to get rid of the first sort — it is enough to perform this sort before starting the recursion: after all, the elements themselves do not change inside the recursion, so there is no need to sort again. With the second sorting a little more difficult to perform, performing it previously will not work. But, remembering the merge sort, which also works on the principle of divide-and-conquer, we can simply embed this sort in our recursion. Let recursion, taking some set of points (as we remember,ordered by pairs ), return the same set, but sorted by the -coordinate. To do this, simply merge (in ) the two results returned by recursive calls. This will result in a set sorted by -coordinate.
Evaluation of the asymptotics
To show that the above algorithm is actually executed in , we need to prove the following fact: .
So, let us consider some point ; recall that the set  is a set of points whose -coordinate lies in the segment , and, moreover, along the  coordinate, the point  itself, and all the points of the set  lie in the band width . In other words, the points we are considering  and  lie in a rectangle of size .
Our task is to estimate the maximum number of points that can lie in this rectangle ; thus, we estimate the maximum size of the set . At the same time, when evaluating, we must not forget that there may be repeated points.
Remember that  was obtained from the results of two recursive calls — on sets  and , and  contains points to the left of the partition line and partially on it,  contains the remaining points of the partition line and points to the right of it. For any pair of points from , as well as from , the distance can not be less than  — otherwise it would mean incorrect operation of the recursive function.
To estimate the maximum number of points in the rectangle  we divide it into two squares , the first square include all points , and the second contains all the others, i.e. . It follows from the above considerations that in each of these squares the distance between any two points is at least .
We show that there are at most four points in each square. For example, this can be done as follows: divide the square into  sub-squares with sides . Then there can be no more than one point in each of these sub-squares (since even the diagonal is equal to , which is less than ). Therefore, there can be no more than  points in the whole square.
So, we have proved that in a rectangle  can not be more than  points, and, therefore, the size of the set  cannot exceed , as required.
Implementation
We introduce a data structure to store a point (its coordinates and a number) and comparison operators required for two types of sorting:
struct pt {
    int x, y, id;
};

struct cmp_x {
    bool operator()(const pt & a, const pt & b) const {
        return a.x < b.x || (a.x == b.x && a.y < b.y);
    }
};

struct cmp_y {
    bool operator()(const pt & a, const pt & b) const {
        return a.y < b.y;
    }
};

int n;
vector<pt> a;

For a convenient implementation of recursion, we introduce an auxiliary function upd_ans(), which will calculate the distance between two points and check whether it is better than the current answer:
double mindist;
pair<int, int> best_pair;

void upd_ans(const pt & a, const pt & b) {
    double dist = sqrt((a.x - b.x)*(a.x - b.x) + (a.y - b.y)*(a.y - b.y));
    if (dist < mindist) {
        mindist = dist;
        best_pair = {a.id, b.id};
    }
}

Finally, the implementation of the recursion itself. It is assumed that before calling it, the array  is already sorted by -coordinate. In recursion we pass just two pointers , which indicate that it should look for the answer for . If the distance between  and  is too small, the recursion must be stopped, and perform a trivial algorithm to find the nearest pair and then sort the subarray by -coordinate.
To merge two sets of points received from recursive calls into one (ordered by -coordinate), we use the standard STL  function, and create an auxiliary buffer (one for all recursive calls). (Using inplace_merge () is impractical because it generally does not work in linear time.)
Finally, the set  is stored in the same array .
vector<pt> t;

void rec(int l, int r) {
    if (r - l <= 3) {
        for (int i = l; i < r; ++i) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < r; ++j) {
                upd_ans(a[i], a[j]);
            }
        }
        sort(a.begin() + l, a.begin() + r, cmp_y());
        return;
    }

    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    int midx = a[m].x;
    rec(l, m);
    rec(m, r);

    merge(a.begin() + l, a.begin() + m, a.begin() + m, a.begin() + r, t.begin(), cmp_y());
    copy(t.begin(), t.begin() + r - l, a.begin() + l);

    int tsz = 0;
    for (int i = l; i < r; ++i) {
        if (abs(a[i].x - midx) < mindist) {
            for (int j = tsz - 1; j >= 0 && a[i].y - t[j].y < mindist; --j)
                upd_ans(a[i], t[j]);
            t[tsz++] = a[i];
        }
    }
}

By the way, if all the coordinates are integer, then at the time of the recursion you can not move to fractional values, and store in  the square of the minimum distance.
In the main program, recursion should be called as follows:
t.resize(n);
sort(a.begin(), a.end(), cmp_x());
mindist = 1E20;
rec(0, n);

Linear time randomized algorithms
A randomized algorithm with linear expected time
An alternative method, originally proposed by Rabin in 1976, arises from a very simple idea to heuristically improve the runtime: We can divide the plane into a grid of  squares, then it is only required to test distances between same-block or adjacent-block points (unless all squares are disconnected from each other, but we will avoid this by design), since any other pair has a larger distance than the two points in the same square.

We will consider only the squares containing at least one point. Denote by  the number of points in each of the  remaining squares. Assuming at least two points are in the same or in adjacent squares, and that there are no duplicated points, the time complexity is . We can look for duplicated points in expected linear time using a hash table, and in the affirmative case, the answer is this pair.

Proof
For the -th square containing  points, the number of pairs inside is . If the -th square is adjacent to the -th square, then we also perform  distance comparisons. Notice that each square has at most  adjacent squares, so we can bound the sum of all comparisons by . 

Now we need to decide on how to set  so that it minimizes .
Choosing d
We need  to be an approximation of the minimum distance . Richard Lipton proposed to sample  distances randomly and choose  to be the smallest of these distances as an approximation for . We now prove that the expected running time of the algorithm is linear.

Proof
Imagine the disposition of points in squares with a particular choice of , say . Consider  a random variable, resulting from our sampling of distances. Let's define  as the cost estimation for a particular disposition when we choose . Now, let's define  such that . What is the probability that such choice  survives the sampling of  independent distances? If a single pair among the sampled ones has distance smaller than , this arrangement will be replaced by the smaller . Inside a square, about  of the pairs would raise a smaller distance (imagine four subsquares in every square; using the pigeonhole principle, at least one subsquare has  points), so we have about  pairs which yield a smaller final . This is, approximately, . On the other hand, there are about  pairs that can be sampled. We have that the probability of sampling a pair with distance smaller than  is at least (approximately) 
\frac{\lambda(x) \, n / 32}{n^2 / 2} = \frac{\lambda(x)/16}{n}
so the probability of at least one such pair being chosen during the  rounds (and therefore finding a smaller ) is 
1 - \left(1 - \frac{\lambda(x)/16}{n}\right)^n \ge 1 - e^{-\lambda(x)/16}
(we have used that  for any real number , check Bernoulli inequalities).  Notice this goes to  exponentially as  increases. This hints that  will be small for a poorly chosen .
We have shown that , or equivalently, . We need to know  to be able to estimate its expected value. We notice that . This is because making the squares smaller only reduces the number of points in each square (splits the points into other squares), and this keeps reducing the sum of squares. Therefore,
\Pr(\lambda(d) \ge \lambda(x)) = \Pr(d \ge x) \le e^{-\lambda(x)/16} \implies \Pr(\lambda(d) \ge t) \le e^{-t/16} \implies \mathbb{E}[\lambda(d)] \le \int_{0}^{+\infty} e^{-t/16} \, \mathrm{d}t = 16
(we have used that , check Stackexchange proof).
Finally, , and the expected running time is , with a reasonable constant factor. 

Implementation of the algorithm
The advantage of this algorithm is that it is straightforward to implement, but still has good performance in practise. We first sample  distances and set  as the minimum of the distances. Then we insert points into the "blocks" by using a hash table from 2D coordinates to a vector of points. Finally, just compute distances between same-block pairs and adjacent-block pairs. Hash table operations have  expected time cost, and therefore our algorithm retains the  expected time cost with an increased constant.
