The correctness follows from the fact that at any moment we already have some pair with distance , so we try to find only new pairs with distance smaller than . Since each square has side , a candidate pair can be at most at a distance of  squares, so for a given point we check candidates in the surrounding  squares. Any point in a square further away will always give a distace larger than .
While this algorithm may look slow, because of recomputing everything multiple times, we can show the total expected cost is linear. 

Proof
Let  the random variable that is  when point  causes a change of  and a recomputation of the data structures, and  if not. It is easy to show that the cost is , since on the -th step we are considering only the first  points. However, turns out that . This is because on the -th step,  is the distance of the closest pair in , and  is the probability of  belonging to the closest pair, which only happens in  pairs out of the  possible pairs (assuming all distances are different), so the probability is at most , since we previously shuffled the points uniformly.
We can therefore see that the expected cost is 
O\!\left(n + \sum_{i=1}^{n} i \Pr(X_i = 1)\right) \le O\!\left(n + \sum_{i=1}^{n} i \frac{2}{i}\right) = O(3n) = O(n) \quad \quad \blacksquare

Generalization: finding a triangle with minimal perimeter
The algorithm described above is interestingly generalized to this problem: among a given set of points, choose three different points so that the sum of pairwise distances between them is the smallest.
In fact, to solve this problem, the algorithm remains the same: we divide the field into two halves of the vertical line, call the solution recursively on both halves, choose the minimum  from the found perimeters, build a strip with the thickness of , and iterate through all triangles that can improve the answer. (Note that the triangle with perimeter  has the longest side .)
