Point location in 
Consider the following problem: you are given a planar subdivision without any vertices of degree one and zero, and a lot of queries.
Each query is a point, for which we should determine the face of the subdivision it belongs to.
We will answer each query in  offline.
This problem may arise when you need to locate some points in a Voronoi diagram or in some simple polygon.
Algorithm
Firstly, for each query point  we want to find such an edge that if the point belongs to any edge, the point lies on the edge we found, otherwise this edge must intersect the line  at some unique point  where  and this  is maximum among all such edges.
The following image shows both cases.

We will solve this problem offline using the sweep line algorithm. Let's iterate over x-coordinates of query points and edges' endpoints in increasing order and keep a set of edges . For each x-coordinate we will add some events beforehand.
The events will be of four types: add, remove, vertical, get.
For each vertical edge (both endpoints have the same x-coordinate) we will add one vertical event for the corresponding x-coordinate.
For every other edge we will add one add event for the minimum of x-coordinates of the endpoints and one remove event for the maximum of x-coordinates of the endpoints.
Finally, for each query point we will add one get event for its x-coordinate.
For each x-coordinate we will sort the events by their types in order (vertical, get, remove, add).
The following image shows all events in sorted order for each x-coordinate.

We will keep two sets during the sweep-line process.
A set  for all non-vertical edges, and one set  especially for the vertical ones.
We will clear the set  at the beginning of processing each x-coordinate.
Now let's process the events for a fixed x-coordinate.

If we got a vertical event, we will simply insert the minimum y-coordinate of the corresponding edge's endpoints to .
If we got a remove or add event, we will remove the corresponding edge from  or add it to .
Finally, for each get event we must check if the point lies on some vertical edge by performing a binary search in .
If the point doesn't lie on any vertical edge, we must find the answer for this query in .
To do this, we again make a binary search.
In order to handle some degenerate cases (e.g. in case of the triangle , ,  when we query the point ), we must answer all get events again after we processed all the events for this x-coordinate and choose the best of two answers.

Now let's choose a comparator for the set .
This comparator should check if one edge doesn't lie above other for every x-coordinate they both cover. Suppose that we have two edges  and . Then the comparator is (in pseudocode):

