Centroid Decomposition
Prerequisite knowledge: Depth First Search (DFS), Divide and Conquer, Trees.
Introduction
Centroid Decomposition is a divide-and-conquer technique on trees. It is used to solve various problems that involve paths in a tree, such as counting paths with certain properties, finding distances, or answering queries on tree paths.
The key idea is to recursively decompose a tree by finding its centroid. This special vertex when removed splits the tree into components, each containing at most half of the original tree's vertices. This guarantees a logarithmic depth of recursion, leading to efficient algorithms.
Properties and Definition of a Centroid
Let's first understand what a centroid is. A centroid of a tree is a vertex whose removal results in no subtree having more than  vertices, where  is the total number of vertices in the tree.

For any given tree with  vertices, either one or two centroids exist. If there are two centroids, they must, as well, be adjacent.
Existence and Uniqueness
Theorem: Every tree has at least one centroid, and at most two centroids. If there are two centroids, they must be adjacent.

Proof
Existence: Start from any vertex and keep moving to the child with the largest subtree. Stop when no child has more than  vertices. At this point, the current vertex  is a centroid because (1) no child's subtree contains more than  vertices (by stopping condition) (2) the "parent side" (all vertices except 's subtree when  was a child) contains at most  vertices (otherwise we wouldn't have moved to  from parent).
It is easy to see that this process always terminates, proving at least one centroid exists.
Uniqueness: Suppose there are two centroids  and . Consider the path between them. When we remove , vertex  must be in a component with at most  vertices. Similarly, when we remove , vertex  must be in a component with at most  vertices. This is only possible if  and  are adjacent; otherwise, removing either would place the other in a component with more than  vertices. This contradicts our initial statement of both centroids being in a component with at most  vertices. Furthermore, if two centroids exist, they must split the tree into two components of exactly  vertices each, which is only possible when  is even.

Properties and Definition of Centroid Decomposition
"Decomposing" the tree then essentially means recursively finding centroids and breaking the tree into subtrees based on the centroid's components. Such a recursive decomposition of the tree into its components creates a unique set of properties:

Decomposition depth: The depth is  because each level at least halves the component size.
Path coverage: Every path in the tree passes through the centroid of some component in the decomposition.

Decomposition Depth
Theorem: The depth, or number of steps, when using centroid decomposition on any given tree is .

Proof
Consider any vertex  in the original tree. We track how many times  can be part of a component during the decomposition process.
At the first level,  is in a component of size . When we remove the centroid of this component,  ends up in a component of size at most  (by the balance property).
At the second level,  is in a component of size at most . Removing this component's centroid places  in a component of size at most .
Continuing this pattern, at the -th level,  is in a component of size at most .
The decomposition stops when component sizes reach 1. This happens when , which gives us .
Therefore, the maximum depth of the centroid decomposition tree is .

Consequence: Since each vertex participates in at most  levels of decomposition, and we process each vertex once at each level, algorithms using centroid decomposition typically have a time complexity factor of  multiplied by the work done per vertex per level.
Path Coverage
Theorem: Every path in the original tree passes through the centroid of some component in the decomposition.

Proof
Consider any path  from vertex  to vertex  in the original tree. We need to show that this path passes through at least one centroid chosen during the decomposition process.
We prove this by induction on the decomposition process.
Base case: At the first level of decomposition, we select the centroid  of the entire tree. If the path  passes through , we are done.
Inductive case: Suppose path  does not pass through . When we remove , the tree splits into multiple components. Since  is a connected path, both  and  must lie in the same component  after removing  (otherwise,  would have to pass through  to connect them, which contradicts our assumption).
Now we recursively decompose component . By the inductive hypothesis applied to component , the path  (which is entirely contained in ) must pass through the centroid of some component in the decomposition of .
This process continues until we find a centroid through which  passes. The process must terminate because at each level, the component containing  gets strictly smaller (by the balance property), and eventually reduces to a single edge or vertex.

Consequence: This property is fundamental to the correctness of centroid decomposition algorithms. It ensures that when we process all paths through each centroid, we cover all possible paths in the tree exactly once at some level of the decomposition. This is why centroid decomposition can solve path-related problems efficiently: every path is considered exactly once, at the level where it first encounters a centroid.
Finding a Centroid
To find a centroid of a tree efficiently:

Calculate subtree sizes for all vertices using Depth First Search (DFS)
Start from any vertex
Find a child  whose subtree contains more than  vertices
Move to  and repeat step 3
If no such child exists, the current vertex is a centroid

Time complexity: .
Space complexity: .
Algorithm Description
When using centroid decomposition, the general flow works as follows:

Find the centroid of the current tree/component
Process all paths passing through this centroid and do any desired calculations
Remove the centroid (mark it as used)
Recursively decompose each resulting subtree

This creates a centroid tree. Each node in this tree represents a centroid from some stage of decomposition. This means that the parent of a centroid (any given node) is the centroid that was found in the larger component containing it. The height of this tree is  as proven before.

For example, in the above image, we have a centroid tree. Each node at each level of the tree is a centroid of that component (e.g. the root is the centroid of the entire tree, the left most child of the root is the centroid of the left most subtree of the root, etc.).
Implementation
Here's an implementation of centroid decomposition solving a specific problem: counting all paths in the tree with length exactly .
In this problem, we're given a tree with  vertices and need to count how many paths have exactly  edges. A path is defined by two distinct vertices.
const int MAXN = 1e5;
vector<int> adj[MAXN];
bool removed[MAXN];
int subtree_size[MAXN];
int K;  // Target path length
long long answer = 0;  // Count of paths with length K

int get_subtree_size(int v, int p = -1) {
    subtree_size[v] = 1;
    for (int u : adj[v]) {
        if (u == p || removed[u]) continue;
        subtree_size[v] += get_subtree_size(u, v);
    }
    return subtree_size[v];
}

int get_centroid(int v, int tree_size, int p = -1) {
    for (int u : adj[v]) {
        if (u == p || removed[u]) continue;
        if (subtree_size[u] * 2 > tree_size)
            return get_centroid(u, tree_size, v);
    }
    return v;
}

void get_distances(int v, int p, int dist, vector<int>& distances) {
    if (dist > K) return;
    distances.push_back(dist);
    for (int u : adj[v]) {
        if (u == p || removed[u]) continue;
        get_distances(u, v, dist + 1, distances);
    }
}

void process_centroid(int centroid) {
    unordered_map<int, int> all_distances;
    all_distances[0] = 1;

    for (int u : adj[centroid]) {
        if (removed[u])
            continue;

        vector<int> current_distances;
        get_distances(u, centroid, 1, current_distances);

        for (int d : current_distances) {
            if (K - d >= 0) {
                answer += (all_distances[K - d] ? all_distances[K - d] : 0);
            }
        }

        for (int d : current_distances) {
            if (all_distances.find(d) == all_distances.end())
                all_distances[d] = 0;
            all_distances[d]++;
        }
    }
}

void decompose(int v) {
    int tree_size = get_subtree_size(v);
    int centroid = get_centroid(v, tree_size);

    process_centroid(centroid);

    removed[centroid] = true;

    for (int u : adj[centroid]) {
        if (!removed[u]) {
            decompose(u);
        }
    }
}

This template can be adapted to solve different problems using centroid decomposition. In this specific case, it solves the problem of counting all paths of length . The strategy is: for each centroid, count paths passing through it by finding pairs of vertices in different subtrees at distances  and  their sum is  (i.e. a path passing through the centroid consists of a vertex in one subtree at distance  from the centroid and a vertex in another subtree at distance  where ). For each distance  in the current subtree, the code counts how many vertices are at distance  in previous subtrees. The optimization skips distances beyond  to avoid unnecessary recursion.
Building the Centroid Tree
If you need to build an explicit centroid tree structure (useful for answering queries):
