D´Esopo-Pape algorithm
Given a graph with  vertices and  edges with weights  and a starting vertex .
The task is to find the shortest path from the vertex  to every other vertex.
The algorithm from D´Esopo-Pape will work faster than Dijkstra's algorithm and the Bellman-Ford algorithm in most cases, and will also work for negative edges.
However not for negative cycles.
Description
Let the array  contain the shortest path lengths, i.e.  is the current length of the shortest path from the vertex  to the vertex .
Initially this array is filled with infinity for every vertex, except .
After the algorithm finishes, this array will contain the shortest distances.
Let the array  contain the current ancestors, i.e.  is the direct ancestor of the vertex  on the current shortest path from  to .
Just like the array , the array  changes gradually during the algorithm and at the end takes its final values.
Now to the algorithm.
At each step three sets of vertices are maintained:

 - vertices, for which the distance has already been calculated (although it might not be the final distance)
 - vertices, for which the distance currently is calculated
 - vertices, for which the distance has not yet been calculated

The vertices in the set  are stored in a bidirectional queue (deque).
At each step of the algorithm we take a vertex from the set  (from the front of the queue).
Let  be the selected vertex.
We put this vertex  into the set .
Then we iterate over all edges coming out of this vertex.
Let  be the second end of the current edge, and  its weight.

If  belongs to , then  is inserted into the set  by inserting it at the back of the queue.
