Lowest Common Ancestor -  and  with  preprocessing
Given a tree . Given queries of the form , for each query you need to find the lowest common ancestor (or least common ancestor), i.e. a vertex  that lies on the path from the root to  and the path from the root to , and the vertex should be the lowest. In other words, the desired vertex  is the most bottom ancestor of  and . It is obvious that their lowest common ancestor lies on a shortest path from  and . Also, if  is the ancestor of ,  is their lowest common ancestor.
The Idea of the Algorithm
Before answering the queries, we need to preprocess the tree.
We make a DFS traversal starting at the root and we build a list  which stores the order of the vertices that we visit (a vertex is added to the list when we first visit it, and after the return of the DFS traversals to its children).
This is also called an Euler tour of the tree.
It is clear that the size of this list will be .
We also need to build an array  which stores for each vertex  its first occurrence in .
That is, the first position in  such that .
Also by using the DFS we can find the height of each node (distance from root to it) and store it in the array .
So how can we answer queries using the Euler tour and the additional two arrays?
Suppose the query is a pair of  and .
Consider the vertices that we visit in the Euler tour between the first visit of  and the first visit of .
It is easy to see, that the  is the vertex with the lowest height on this path.
We already noticed, that the LCA has to be part of the shortest path between  and .
Clearly it also has to be the vertex with the smallest height.
And in the Euler tour we essentially use the shortest path, except that we additionally visit all subtrees that we find on the path.
But all vertices in these subtrees are lower in the tree than the LCA and therefore have a larger height.
So the  can be uniquely determined by finding the vertex with the smallest height in the Euler tour between  and .
Let's illustrate this idea.
Consider the following graph and the Euler tour with the corresponding heights:

\begin{array}{|l|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
\text{Vertices:}   & 1 & 2 & 5 & 2 & 6 & 2 & 1 & 3 & 1 & 4 & 7 & 4 & 1 \\ \hline
\text{Heights:} & 1 & 2 & 3 & 2 & 3 & 2 & 1 & 2 & 1 & 2 & 3 & 2 & 1 \\ \hline
\end{array}
The tour starting at vertex  and ending at  we visit the vertices .
Among those vertices the vertex  has the lowest height, therefore .
To recap:
to answer a query we just need to find the vertex with smallest height in the array  in the range from  to .
Thus, the LCA problem is reduced to the RMQ problem (finding the minimum in an range problem).
Using Sqrt-Decomposition, it is possible to obtain a solution answering each query in  with preprocessing in  time.
Using a Segment Tree you can answer each query in  with preprocessing in  time.
Since there will almost never be any update to the stored values, a Sparse Table might be a better choice, allowing  query answering with  build time.
Implementation
In the following implementation of the LCA algorithm a Segment Tree is used.
struct LCA {
    vector<int> height, euler, first, segtree;
    vector<bool> visited;
    int n;

    LCA(vector<vector<int>> &adj, int root = 0) {
        n = adj.size();
        height.resize(n);
        first.resize(n);
        euler.reserve(n * 2);
        visited.assign(n, false);
        dfs(adj, root);
        int m = euler.size();
        segtree.resize(m * 4);
        build(1, 0, m - 1);
    }

    void dfs(vector<vector<int>> &adj, int node, int h = 0) {
        visited[node] = true;
        height[node] = h;
        first[node] = euler.size();
        euler.push_back(node);
        for (auto to : adj[node]) {
            if (!visited[to]) {
                dfs(adj, to, h + 1);
                euler.push_back(node);
            }
        }
    }

    void build(int node, int b, int e) {
        if (b == e) {
            segtree[node] = euler[b];
        } else {
            int mid = (b + e) / 2;
            build(node << 1, b, mid);
            build(node << 1 | 1, mid + 1, e);
            int l = segtree[node << 1], r = segtree[node << 1 | 1];
            segtree[node] = (height[l] < height[r]) ? l : r;
        }
    }

    int query(int node, int b, int e, int L, int R) {
        if (b > R || e < L)
            return -1;
        if (b >= L && e <= R)
            return segtree[node];
        int mid = (b + e) >> 1;

        int left = query(node << 1, b, mid, L, R);
        int right = query(node << 1 | 1, mid + 1, e, L, R);
        if (left == -1) return right;
        if (right == -1) return left;
        return height[left] < height[right] ? left : right;
    }

    int lca(int u, int v) {
        int left = first[u], right = first[v];
        if (left > right)
            swap(left, right);
        return query(1, 0, euler.size() - 1, left, right);
    }
};

