Lowest Common Ancestor - Tarjan's off-line algorithm
We have a tree  with  nodes and we have  queries of the form .
For each query  we want to find the lowest common ancestor of the vertices  and , i.e. the node that is an ancestor of both  and  and has the greatest depth in the tree.
The node  is also an ancestor of , so the LCA can also be one of the two nodes.
In this article we will solve the problem off-line, i.e. we assume that all queries are known in advance, and we therefore answer the queries in any order we like.
The following algorithm allows to answer all  queries in  total time, i.e. for sufficiently large  in  for each query.
Algorithm
The algorithm is named after Robert Tarjan, who discovered it in 1979 and also made many other contributions to the Disjoint Set Union data structure, which will be heavily used in this algorithm.
The algorithm answers all queries with one DFS traversal of the tree.
Namely a query  is answered at node , if node  has already been visited previously, or vice versa.
So let's assume we are currently at node , we have already made recursive DFS calls, and also already visited the second node  from the query .
Let's learn how to find the LCA of these two nodes.
Note that  is either the node  or one of its ancestors.
So we need to find the lowest node among the ancestors of  (including ), for which the node  is a descendant. 
Also note that for a fixed  the visited nodes of the tree split into a set of disjoint sets. 
Each ancestor  of node  has his own set containing this node and all subtrees with roots in those of its children who are not part of the path from  to the root of the tree.
The set which contains the node  determines the :
the LCA is the representative of the set, namely the node on lies on the path between  and the root of the tree.
We only need to learn to efficiently maintain all these sets.
For this purpose we apply the data structure DSU.
To be able to apply Union by rank, we store the real representative (the value on the path between  and the root of the tree) of each set in the array ancestor.
Let's discuss the implementation of the DFS.
Let's assume we are currently visiting the node .
We place the node in a new set in the DSU, ancestor[v] = v.
As usual we process all children of .
For this we must first recursively call DFS from that node, and then add this node with all its subtree to the set of .
This can be done with the function union_sets and the following assignment ancestor[find_set(v)] = v (this is necessary, because union_sets might change the representative of the set).
Finally after processing all children we can answer all queries of the form  for which  has been already visited.
The answer to the query, i.e. the LCA of  and , will be the node ancestor[find_set(u)].
It is easy to see that a query will only be answered once.
Let's us determine the time complexity of this algorithm. 
Firstly we have  because of the DFS.
Secondly  we have the function calls of union_sets which happen  times, resulting also in .
And thirdly we have the calls of find_set for every query, which gives .
So in total the time complexity is , which means that for sufficiently large  this corresponds to  for answering one query.
Implementation
Here is an implementation of this algorithm.
The implementation of DSU has been not included, as it can be used without any modifications.
vector<vector<int>> adj;
vector<vector<int>> queries;
vector<int> ancestor;
vector<bool> visited;

void dfs(int v)
{
    visited[v] = true;
    ancestor[v] = v;
    for (int u : adj[v]) {
        if (!visited[u]) {
            dfs(u);
            union_sets(v, u);
            ancestor[find_set(v)] = v;
        }
    }
    for (int other_node : queries[v]) {
        if (visited[other_node])
            cout << "LCA of " << v << " and " << other_node
                 << " is " << ancestor[find_set(other_node)] << ".\n";
    }
}

