Minimum spanning tree - Kruskal with Disjoint Set Union
For an explanation of the MST problem and the Kruskal algorithm, first see the main article on Kruskal's algorithm.
In this article we will consider the data structure "Disjoint Set Union" for implementing Kruskal's algorithm, which will allow the algorithm to achieve the time complexity of .
Description
Just as in the simple version of the Kruskal algorithm, we sort all the edges of the graph in non-decreasing order of weights.
Then put each vertex in its own tree (i.e. its set) via calls to the make_set function - it will take a total of .
We iterate through all the edges (in sorted order) and for each edge determine whether the ends belong to different trees (with two find_set calls in  each).
Finally, we need to perform the union of the two trees (sets), for which the DSU union_sets function will be called - also in .
So we get the total time complexity of  = .
Implementation
Here is an implementation of Kruskal's algorithm with Union by Rank.
vector<int> parent, rank;

void make_set(int v) {
    parent[v] = v;
    rank[v] = 0;
}

int find_set(int v) {
    if (v == parent[v])
        return v;
    return parent[v] = find_set(parent[v]);
}

void union_sets(int a, int b) {
    a = find_set(a);
    b = find_set(b);
    if (a != b) {
        if (rank[a] < rank[b])
            swap(a, b);
        parent[b] = a;
        if (rank[a] == rank[b])
            rank[a]++;
    }
}

struct Edge {
    int u, v, weight;
    bool operator<(Edge const& other) {
        return weight < other.weight;
    }
};

int n;
vector<Edge> edges;

int cost = 0;
vector<Edge> result;
parent.resize(n);
rank.resize(n);
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    make_set(i);

sort(edges.begin(), edges.end());

for (Edge e : edges) {
    if (find_set(e.u) != find_set(e.v)) {
        cost += e.weight;
        result.push_back(e);
        union_sets(e.u, e.v);
    }
}

Notice: since the MST will contain exactly  edges, we can stop the for loop once we found that many.
