Lyndon factorization
Lyndon factorization
First let us define the notion of the Lyndon factorization.
A string is called simple (or a Lyndon word), if it is strictly smaller than any of its own nontrivial suffixes.
Examples of simple strings are: , , , , , , .
It can be shown that a string is simple, if and only if it is strictly smaller than all its nontrivial cyclic shifts.
Next, let there be a given string .
The Lyndon factorization of the string  is a factorization , where all strings  are simple, and they are in non-increasing order .
It can be shown, that for any string such a factorization exists and that it is unique.
Duval algorithm
The Duval algorithm constructs the Lyndon factorization in  time using  additional memory.
First let us introduce another notion:
a string  is called pre-simple, if it has the form , where  is a simple string and  is a prefix of  (possibly empty).
A simple string is also pre-simple.
The Duval algorithm is greedy.
At any point during its execution, the string  will actually be divided into three strings , where the Lyndon factorization for  is already found and finalized, the string  is pre-simple (and we know the length of the simple string in it), and  is completely untouched.
In each iteration the Duval algorithm takes the first character of the string  and tries to append it to the string .
It  is no longer pre-simple, then the Lyndon factorization for some part of  becomes known, and this part goes to .
Let's describe the algorithm in more detail.
The pointer  will always point to the beginning of the string .
The outer loop will be executed as long as .
Inside the loop we use two additional pointers,  which points to the beginning of , and  which points to the current character that we are currently comparing to.
We want to add the character  to the string , which requires a comparison with the character .
There can be three different cases:

: if this is the case, then adding the symbol  to  doesn't violate its pre-simplicity.
  So we simply increment the pointers  and .
: here, the string  becomes simple.
  We can increment  and reset  back to the beginning of , so that the next character can be compared with the beginning of the simple word.
: the string  is no longer pre-simple.
  Therefore we will split the pre-simple string  into its simple strings and the remainder, possibly empty.
  The simple string will have the length .
  In the next iteration we start again with the remaining .

Implementation
Here we present the implementation of the Duval algorithm, which will return the desired Lyndon factorization of a given string .
vector<string> duval(string const& s) {
    int n = s.size();
    int i = 0;
    vector<string> factorization;
    while (i < n) {
        int j = i + 1, k = i;
        while (j < n && s[k] <= s[j]) {
            if (s[k] < s[j])
                k = i;
            else
                k++;
            j++;
        }
        while (i <= k) {
            factorization.push_back(s.substr(i, j - k));
            i += j - k;
        }
    }
    return factorization;
}

Complexity
Let us estimate the running time of this algorithm.
The outer while loop does not exceed  iterations, since at the end of each iteration  increases.
Also the second inner while loop runs in , since is only outputs the final factorization.
So we are only interested in the first inner while loop.
How many iterations does it perform in the worst case?
It's easy to see that the simple words that we identify in each iteration of the outer loop are longer than the remainder that we additionally compared.
Therefore also the sum of the remainders will be smaller than , which means that we only perform at most  iterations of the first inner while loop.
In fact the total number of character comparisons will not exceed .
Finding the smallest cyclic shift
Let there be a string .
We construct the Lyndon factorization for the string  (in  time).
We will look for a simple string in the factorization, which starts at a position less than  (i.e. it starts in the first instance of ), and ends in a position greater than or equal to  (i.e. in the second instance) of ).
It is stated, that the position of the start of this simple string will be the beginning of the desired smallest cyclic shift.
This can be easily verified using the definition of the Lyndon decomposition.
The beginning of the simple block can be found easily - just remember the pointer  at the beginning of each iteration of the outer loop, which indicated the beginning of the current pre-simple string.
So we get the following implementation:
string min_cyclic_string(string s) {
    s += s;
    int n = s.size();
    int i = 0, ans = 0;
    while (i < n / 2) {
        ans = i;
        int j = i + 1, k = i;
        while (j < n && s[k] <= s[j]) {
            if (s[k] < s[j])
                k = i;
            else
                k++;
            j++;
        }
        while (i <= k)
            i += j - k;
    }
    return s.substr(ans, n / 2);
}

