Number of different substrings
We preprocess the string  by computing the suffix array and the LCP array.
Using this information we can compute the number of different substrings in the string.
To do this, we will think about which new substrings begin at position , then at , etc.
In fact we take the suffixes in sorted order and see what prefixes give new substrings.
Thus we will not overlook any by accident.
Because the suffixes are sorted, it is clear that the current suffix  will give new substrings for all its prefixes, except for the prefixes that coincide with the suffix .
Thus, all its prefixes except the first  one.
Since the length of the current suffix is ,  new prefixes start at .
Summing over all the suffixes, we get the final answer:
\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} (n - p[i]) - \sum_{i=0}^{n-2} \text{lcp}[i] = \frac{n^2 + n}{2} - \sum_{i=0}^{n-2} \text{lcp}[i]
